betterquesting:10.desc:8: As expected, you can't rely on basic vanilla tools. Time to put your tinkering skills to work.
You can either go melter or full-fledged smeltry. Either way you're gonna need some of these.
Aenia - A moon of endless grassy plains
Build your first rocket and visit Aenia's sister moons in orbit of the gas giant, Nodiclite (Interact with built rocket to complete task)
Zuniter - A boiling-hot planet that some would describe as "hellish"
Oziri - Frigid plains punctured by giant crystalline structures. One of the only known sources of dilithium crystals.
Gitera - A mineral-rich planet. Even the flora has taken on gem-like properties.
Build a warp-drive to undertake the long journey between planets around Beta Crion, a class G star.
Cruathea - A lush planet dominated by slime-based lifeforms.
Senguvis - The homeworld of a long-forgotten civilization. For some, a warning to the intelligent beings of the galaxy, to others a great looting opportunity.
Satis - The high concentration of radioactive elements makes this moon almost uninhabitable. Wear radiation protection and watch out for frequent storms.
Xeovis - A planet of dense swamplands. Careful, the inhabitants found themselves the victims of some sort of inter-dimensional accident leaving them... changed.
Neobos - An ocean planet. Any exposed land has been stripped bare by near-constant storms.
Zumadus - A perfect balance between the relentless waters of Neobos and the hot sands of Kubos. A tropical paradise.
Kubos - The complete opposite of its mother Neobos - endless dry deserts.
Place an upgrade in an artifact slot of your warp controller to be able to warp to A class star systems.

Strillion - That's no gas giant. Left behind by the death of something ancient and colossal, this impossibly massive xp orb can be harvested for essence. Try not to think of the gravitational catastrophe that will occur if/when it despawns.
Sevima - A barren moon with high volcanic activity. The magma is rich with rare minerals, if you can find a way to extract them.
Docides - A massive asteroid captured by Strillon during its formation.
Roletov - Much of the planet has been corrupted by some unknown pathogen that alters mineral and living alike. Locals refer to it as "defilement."
Chiyopra - Despite the sun being perpetually blocked out by a dense fog, this planet is teeming with life.
Ulillon - Whether they were left behind or were directly involved in the migration of their creators, this planet is now overrun by synthetic lifeforms.

Ginus - A desert moon inhabited by the people known only as "Villagers" - presumably decendants of colonizers from Ulillon. There may be villagers able to help you with android tech, but they will be shunned by other Villagers so you will likely find them wandering the desert.
Aetune - An icy planet colonized by villagers. Local bandit leaders are rumored to have their hands on ancient tech from Ulillon.
Troathea - Another planet colonized by the Villagers. Local bandit leaders are rumored to have their hands on ancient tech from Ulillon.

Upgrade your warp drive to travel to class O star systems. WARNING: Cibru is emitting unusual energy readings. Zatera is far enough away to approach, but the inner planets may require additional warp drive shielding.
Zatera - A swampy planet with visible corruption from the strange energy emitted by Cibru.
Olomia - Forests and mountains darkened by the corruption of Cibru. Reaching this planet will require a Coralium Catalyst in the warp controller to help shield it.
Theliuq - A green wasteland infested by corrupted inhabitants. Reaching Theliuq will require an Oblivion Catalyst in the warp controller.

Ruclite - If the corrupting influence of Cibru wasn't enough, this planet has been ravaged by a deadly virus known as the "dread plague." Reaching Ruclite will require coralium plating in the warp controller.
Gogrov - A planet plunged into darkness. Only the most dangerous inhabitants have managed to survive. Reaching Gogrov will require Dreadium Plating in the warp controller.
Thibos - On the surface, a rocky wasteland. Deep below is a thriving ecosystem sustained by geothermal energy.
Caopra - Vast azure forests. The locals are known to make tools from rare metals - melting these down may be to only source.

Tenao - Vast icy wastelands punctuated by massive mountain ranges. The rock here contains high concentrations of minerals, including very rare ones. Unfortunately they are all finely blended so it will take some serious processing to extract what you need.
One final warp drive upgrade will allow you to jump into the vicinity of black holes.
Tulion - Whether due to proximity to Dros or not, this planet is home to strange interdimensional anomalies. If you crack one open, be careful. Who knows where they might lead to.
The seared heater isn't quite hot enough to melt iron. You'll need a high furnace for that. This will also be your first option for creating steel.

You have a passable rocket with enough fuel to get you off the planet. You won't immediately suffocate when you leave the atmosphere. Time to stick a planet id chip in the computer, pick a target, and blast off! No seatbelts required!

Well... it's more about defining the build area for your rocket than actually launching. The launch pad defines the horizontal space (can be any size) and a single column of structure towers tacked on the side determines the vertical space (again, any size).
Place it adjacent to your build area (launch pad), give it power, click scan, and then it will tell you if you should quit your day job as a rocket scientist or not.

What's deadlier than a zombie and [OVERFLOW ERROR] times bigger? The vacuum of space. Use the suit workstation to add upgrades to your suit (i.e. put the low-pressure tank in your chestpiece to hold oxygen).
The cheapest (but slowest) way to obtain oxygen is with an oxygen collector. Use it to fill a gas charge pad which you can then stand on to fill your space suit.
It's not ideal, but this is the best you can do right now for fuel.

You need 4 things: engines, fuel storage, guidance computer, a comfy mat. Based on your design, you will need more of the first two. The rocket assembler will tell you what you are missing. Keep in mind while you can add any blocks you want (including storage) it will add weight.
It looks like a normal piston, but place a block between the business end and some obsidian to flatten it with the flick of a lever!
Go to the Purple Agate Swamp on Gitera and make some slimy friends. Then murder them. You might find them deep underground sometimes too.

The restructurer can be used to convert crystals into other kinds of crystals. It needs two types of fuels: "glittering" and "shining" i.e. glitter blocks and pink essence repectively. JEI is a little tricky with this... you'll have to look at the crafting uses of these examples and click "Show All Recipes" to get a full list of the acceptable fuels.
The purifier will seperate the goldstone from corrupted materials. It needs the same fuels as the restructurer plus an additional type: "nulling" i.e. tektite.
Goldstone dust is an uncommon drop from leaves in the Goldtonelands. You can also get whole chunks from the resident contorted nagas.

This is your assigned textbook. It will show you how to build all the equipment for your lab. Don't worry, it won't set you back $700. Just slap a test tube on some paper, sprinkle a little redstone dust and poof!
Turns out building a machine to put together delicate electronics is easier than smashing the parts together on a wooden table.
Shift+right-click to choose your machine (click and drag ui to scroll), then right click to place a guide in the world. Shift+scroll wheel to rotate through layers.

betterquesting:10.desc:8: No Description
Link this to an unmanned rocket (using a linking tool) to be able to launch it.
No Description

Build a satellite to collect distance data. These are the minimum components you need. It's up to you to add more power gen/storage or data storage as you see fit. Distance data is used in the observatory to run asteroid scans and can also be used in the astrobody data processor to decrease the likelihood of completely missing an asteroid when attempting to mine it.
Composition data is used to increase the quality of your haul when asteroid mining (more ores vs trash like cobblestone).
Mass data helps increase the overall size of your haul when asteroid mining.
The observatory can be used to find asteroids at night for the cost of 100 distance data. After selecting one, you can program an asteroid chip to target it.

Takes a programmed asteroid chip from the observatory and upgrades it with data received from satellites (distance, composition, and mass) to improve the success of mining missions. Data can be transferred manually with data storage units or by using wireless transceivers (although these can sometimes be buggy) and a linker.
For all your linking needs!

Build a new unmanned rocket or uprade an old one with drills and storage. Then all you have to do is place a programmed asteroid chip (upgraded in the astrobody data processor to your satisfaction) in the guidance computer, make sure it's fueled, and click launch in the linked rocket monitoring station. It will return after a while with your resources (more drills = less time)!

Tired of wasting fuel flying back and forth between moons? Build a space elevator on each moon, place space elevator chips in each, and then use a linker to pair (each chip can store multiple destinations)! Then just power one up, choose a destination, stand in the pod and let the magic happen.

There's no need to haul items back and forth between moons when you can just fire them at a high velocity from a railgun! To set the destination of a railgun link a linker to the target railgun, and then place that linker into the sender. A single railgun can both send and receive items, and can even work with other railguns on the same planet.
No Description
This has multiple uses, but extracting niter from sandstone might be the most important.
Using this method, you should be able to make enough glowstone to get the machinery you need to get a rocket off the ground and find a place to mine it directly.
This machine is useful for breaking down uninspected mineral into different materials. However, it is also a ver efficient way to produce cracked coal.
Provided you use actual lenses instead of glass in your observatory, you should be able to see a good number of different asteroids right away.
Upgrading the motor in your observatory will allow you to find more types of asteroids
No Description
The rarest of asteroids will be difficult to find even with a perfected observatory
Rich with light metals like aluminum and tin,
Contains highly electrically conductive metals like copper and small amounts of gold.
The only source of titanium ore within rocket range of Nodiclite.
These are some of the most common asteroids, with a generous amount of iron and traces of nickel.
Water is finite on the moons of Nodiclite. While you can't reach other planets yet, you can still go just far enough to grab ice-rich asteroids for ice to melt down.
Highly dense asteroid with concentrations of lead and boron.
An asteroid composed entirely of a strange black stone.
Large amounts of coal with diamonds mixed in.
A blend of blue and green - high concentrations of lapis and emerald gems.
Just... very shiny. One of the only sources of platinum.
Iridium is exceedingly rare in this galaxy.
